    slug: "how-to-choose-medspa-guide",
    title: "How to Choose a Medspa: 10 Things to Look For",
    metaTitle: "How to Choose a Medspa: 10 Essential Criteria",
    metaDescription: "Choosing the right medspa matters for your safety and results. Here are 10 critical things to evaluate before booking your first appointment at any medspa.",
    excerpt: "Your choice of medspa directly impacts your safety and results. Before you book anywhere, here are ten critical factors to evaluate, from medical oversight to technology to the questions they should welcome.",
    date: "March 15, 2026",
    author: "Rani Beauty Clinic Team",
    authorCredentials: "Licensed Aesthetic Professionals",
    category: "Patient Education",
    content: `Choosing a medspa is a more consequential decision than most people realize. Unlike a traditional spa where the worst outcome is a disappointing facial, medspa treatments involve medical devices, prescription products, and procedures that can produce complications when performed improperly. The right medspa can deliver transformative results safely. The wrong one can cause harm that takes months or years to correct.

Here are ten things to evaluate before booking your first appointment at any medspa.

1. Verify the Medical Director

Every legitimate medspa operates under the supervision of a licensed physician who serves as the medical director. This is not optional. It is a legal requirement in Washington State and most other states. But the level of involvement varies dramatically.

Some medical directors are actively engaged in the practice, establishing protocols, supervising staff, and being available for complications. Others lend their name to the practice and are rarely present. Ask who the medical director is, what their specialty is, and how involved they are in daily operations. A board-certified physician who is actively engaged in the practice represents a significantly higher standard of care.

At Rani Beauty Clinic, Dr. Alexander Landfield serves as our medical director. He is a board-certified neurologist who is actively involved in clinical oversight and treatment protocols.

2. Research Provider Credentials

The person performing your treatment matters as much as the treatment itself. Ask about their specific training, how long they have been performing the procedure you are considering, and how many treatments they have performed. Legitimate providers welcome these questions and will answer them directly.

Different states have different scope of practice rules. In Washington, nurse practitioners, physician assistants, registered nurses, and licensed aestheticians can perform various medspa treatments within their scope, under physician supervision. What matters is appropriate training, experience, and supervision.

3. Look for FDA-Cleared Devices

The devices used for your treatment should be FDA-cleared for their indicated uses. Ask specifically what device will be used for your treatment and whether it is FDA-cleared. This is a basic safety standard. Clinics using off-brand or imported devices that lack FDA clearance are cutting corners on safety.

4. Evaluate the Consultation Process

A quality medspa will offer a thorough consultation before recommending treatment. During this consultation, you should expect a review of your medical history, a discussion of your concerns and goals, an honest assessment of what treatment can achieve, a discussion of risks and potential complications, and clear pricing with no hidden fees.

If a medspa is willing to perform treatment without a proper consultation, or if the consultation feels like a high-pressure sales pitch, consider these warning signs.

5. Assess Cleanliness and Professionalism

Visit the clinic before committing to treatment. The environment should be clean, professional, and organized. Treatment rooms should appear sterile. Staff should be wearing appropriate attire and following hygiene protocols. The overall atmosphere should feel clinical, not casual.

6. Review Before-and-After Photos

Ask to see before-and-after photos of actual patients treated at the clinic, not stock photos or manufacturer-provided images. Consistent, well-documented patient results demonstrate both the quality of treatment and the clinic's commitment to tracking outcomes. Photos should show realistic results, not overly dramatic transformations that may indicate editing.

7. Understand Their Complication Protocol

Complications can occur with any medical aesthetic treatment, even in the best hands. What distinguishes a quality medspa is how they handle complications. Ask what happens if you experience a side effect or complication. Is a physician available? Is there an after-hours contact? Do they have protocols for managing adverse events? A medspa that dismisses the possibility of complications is more concerning than one that openly acknowledges them and has protocols in place.

8. Check Online Reviews and Reputation

Read reviews on Google, Yelp, and RealSelf. Pay attention to patterns rather than individual reviews. Consistent praise for communication, results, and professionalism is a positive signal. Consistent complaints about the same issues suggest systemic problems. Also note how the clinic responds to negative reviews. Professional, empathetic responses indicate a practice that takes patient feedback seriously.

9. Evaluate Pricing Transparency

A reputable medspa provides clear, upfront pricing. You should know what a treatment costs before you commit to it. Be cautious of clinics that require an in-person visit before providing any pricing information, use high-pressure closing tactics, or offer prices that seem too good to be true.

At Rani Beauty Clinic, our pricing is straightforward. HydraFacial at $275. VI Peel at $395. PRX-T33 at $495. RF Microneedling at $495 to $850. Sofwave at $2,750 to $4,500. We believe transparent pricing builds trust.

10. Trust Your Instincts

After evaluating all the objective factors, trust your instinct. You should feel comfortable, respected, and heard at your medspa. If something feels off during the consultation, if the provider seems dismissive, if the sales pressure feels uncomfortable, or if questions are met with evasion, those feelings are worth listening to.

Choosing a medspa is a partnership. You are entrusting your appearance and your health to a team of professionals. That team should earn your trust through transparency, competence, and genuine care for your outcomes. At Rani Beauty Clinic, we welcome every question on this list because we built our practice to answer them all confidently.`,
